events.description: Roman emperor Caligula accepts the titles of the Principate, bestowed on him by the Senate.
events.html: • AD 37 – Roman emperor Caligula accepts the titles of the Principate, bestowed on him by the Senate.[1]

events.description: After assassinating the Roman Emperor Pertinax, his Praetorian Guards auction off the throne to Didius Julianus.
events.html: • 193 – After assassinating the Roman Emperor Pertinax, his Praetorian Guards auction off the throne to Didius Julianus.[2]

events.description: Roman Emperor Valentinian I appoints his brother Flavius Valens co-emperor.
events.html: • 364 – Roman Emperor Valentinian I appoints his brother Flavius Valens co-emperor.[3]

events.description: The Great German Pilgrimage, which had been under attack by Bedouin bandits for three days, is rescued by the Fatimid governor of Ramla.
events.html: • 1065 – The Great German Pilgrimage, which had been under attack by Bedouin bandits for three days, is rescued by the Fatimid governor of Ramla.[4]

events.description: The foundation stone of Valletta, Malta's capital city, is laid by Jean Parisot de Valette, Grand Master of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta.
events.html: • 1566 – The foundation stone of Valletta, Malta's capital city, is laid[5] by Jean Parisot de Valette, Grand Master of the Sovereign Military Order of Malta.[6]

entities.name: List of Grand Masters of the Knights Hospitaller

events.description: Juan Bautista de Anza finds the site for the Presidio of San Francisco.
events.html: • 1776 – Juan Bautista de Anza finds the site for the Presidio of San Francisco.[7]

events.description: Partitions of Poland: The Duchy of Courland and Semigallia, a northern fief of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, ceases to exist and becomes part of Imperial Russia.
events.html: • 1795 – Partitions of Poland: The Duchy of Courland and Semigallia, a northern fief of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, ceases to exist and becomes part of Imperial Russia.[8]

events.description: Treaty of Florence is signed, ending the war between the French Republic and the Kingdom of Naples.
events.html: • 1801 – Treaty of Florence is signed, ending the war between the French Republic and the Kingdom of Naples.[9]

events.description: Heinrich Wilhelm Matthäus Olbers discovers 2 Pallas, the second asteroid ever to be discovered.
events.html: • 1802 – Heinrich Wilhelm Matthäus Olbers discovers 2 Pallas, the second asteroid ever to be discovered.[10]

events.description: Peninsular War: France defeats Spain in the Battle of Medellín.
events.html: • 1809 – Peninsular War: France defeats Spain in the Battle of Medellín.[11]

events.description: War of 1812: In the Battle of Valparaíso, two American naval vessels are captured by two Royal Navy vessels.
events.html: • 1814 – War of 1812: In the Battle of Valparaíso, two American naval vessels are captured by two Royal Navy vessels.[12]

events.description: First concert of the Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Otto Nicolai.
events.html: • 1842 – First concert of the Vienna Philharmonic Orchestra, conducted by Otto Nicolai.[13]

events.description: Crimean War: France and Britain declare war on Russia.
events.html: • 1854 – Crimean War: France and Britain declare war on Russia.[14]

events.description: First Taranaki War: The Battle of Waireka begins.
events.html: • 1860 – First Taranaki War: The Battle of Waireka begins.[15]

events.description: American Civil War: In the Battle of Glorieta Pass, Union forces stop the Confederate invasion of the New Mexico Territory. The battle began on March 26.
events.html: • 1862 – American Civil War: In the Battle of Glorieta Pass, Union forces stop the Confederate invasion of the New Mexico Territory. The battle began on March 26.[16]

events.description: Henri Fabre becomes the first person to fly a seaplane, the Fabre Hydravion, after taking off from water runway Étang le Barre, near Marseille.
events.html: • 1910 – Henri Fabre becomes the first person to fly a seaplane, the Fabre Hydravion, after taking off from water runway Étang le Barre, near Marseille.[17]

events.description: General John J. Pershing, during World War I, cancels 42nd 'Rainbow' Division's orders to Rolampont for further training and diverted it to the occupy the Baccarat sector. Rainbow Division becomes "the first American division to take over an entire sector on its own, which it held longer than any other American division-occupied sector alone for a period of three months".
events.html: • 1918 – General John J. Pershing, during World War I, cancels 42nd 'Rainbow' Division's orders to Rolampont for further training and diverted it to the occupy the Baccarat sector.[18] Rainbow Division becomes "the first American division to take over an entire sector on its own, which it held longer than any other American division-occupied sector alone for a period of three months".[19]

events.description: Finnish Civil War: On the so-called "Bloody Maundy Thursday of Tampere", the Whites force the Reds to attack the city center, where the city's fiercest battles being fought in Kalevankangas with large casualties on both sides. During the same day, an explosion at the Red headquarters of Tampere kills several commanders.
events.html: • 1918 – Finnish Civil War: On the so-called "Bloody Maundy Thursday of Tampere", the Whites force the Reds to attack the city center, where the city's fiercest battles being fought in Kalevankangas with large casualties on both sides. During the same day, an explosion at the Red headquarters of Tampere kills several commanders.[20][21]

events.description: Palm Sunday tornado outbreak of 1920 affects the Great Lakes region and Deep South states.
events.html: • 1920 – Palm Sunday tornado outbreak of 1920 affects the Great Lakes region and Deep South states.[22]

events.description: The Imperial Airways biplane City of Liverpool is believed to be the first airliner lost to sabotage when a passenger sets a fire on board.
events.html: • 1933 – The Imperial Airways biplane City of Liverpool is believed to be the first airliner lost to sabotage when a passenger sets a fire on board.[23]

events.description: Spanish Civil War: Generalissimo Francisco Franco conquers Madrid after a three-year siege.
events.html: • 1939 – Spanish Civil War: Generalissimo Francisco Franco conquers Madrid after a three-year siege.[24]

events.description: World War II: First day of the Battle of Cape Matapan in Greece between the navies of the United Kingdom and Australia, and the Royal Italian navy.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: First day of the Battle of Cape Matapan in Greece between the navies of the United Kingdom and Australia, and the Royal Italian navy.[25]

events.description: World War II: A British combined force permanently disables the Louis Joubert Lock in Saint-Nazaire in order to keep the German battleship Tirpitz away from the mid-ocean convoy lanes.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: A British combined force permanently disables the Louis Joubert Lock in Saint-Nazaire in order to keep the German battleship Tirpitz away from the mid-ocean convoy lanes.[26]

events.description: Cold War: The United States Department of State releases the Acheson–Lilienthal Report, outlining a plan for the international control of nuclear power.
events.html: • 1946 – Cold War: The United States Department of State releases the Acheson–Lilienthal Report, outlining a plan for the international control of nuclear power.[27]

events.description: The State Council of the People's Republic of China dissolves the government of Tibet.
events.html: • 1959 – The State Council of the People's Republic of China dissolves the government of Tibet.[28]

entities.name: State Council of the People's Republic of China

events.description: ČSA Flight 511 crashes in Igensdorf, Germany, killing 52.
events.html: • 1961 – ČSA Flight 511 crashes in Igensdorf, Germany, killing 52.[29]

events.description: An Mw  7.4 earthquake in Chile sets off a series of tailings dam failures, burying the town of El Cobre and killing at least 500 people.
events.html: • 1965 – An Mw  7.4 earthquake in Chile sets off a series of tailings dam failures, burying the town of El Cobre and killing at least 500 people.[30]

entities.name: 1965 Valparaíso earthquake and the El Cobre dam failures

events.description: Brazilian high school student Edson Luís de Lima Souto is killed by military police at a student protest.
events.html: • 1968 – Brazilian high school student Edson Luís de Lima Souto is killed by military police at a student protest.[31]

events.description: Greek poet and Nobel Prize laureate Giorgos Seferis makes a famous statement on the BBC World Service opposing the junta in Greece.
events.html: • 1969 – Greek poet and Nobel Prize laureate Giorgos Seferis makes a famous statement on the BBC World Service opposing the junta in Greece.[32]

events.description: An earthquake strikes western Turkey at about 23:05 local time, killing 1,086 and injuring at least 1,200.
events.html: • 1970 – An earthquake strikes western Turkey at about 23:05 local time, killing 1,086 and injuring at least 1,200.[33]

events.description: The US Supreme Court hands down 5–3 decision in Stump v. Sparkman, a controversial case involving involuntary sterilization and judicial immunity.

entities.name: Supreme Court of the United States

events.description: A coolant leak at the Three Mile Island's Unit 2 nuclear reactor outside Harrisburg, Pennsylvania leads to the core overheating and a partial meltdown.
